{{short description|Condition in which a parasite infects the gastro-intestinal tract of humans and other animals}} {{Medref|date=December 2017}}
{{Infobox disease | name = Intestinal parasite | image = File:Blausen 0432 GastroIntestinalSystem.png|thumb| | alt = | caption = Human gastro-intestinal system | field = [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|Infectious disease]] | DiseasesDB = | ICD10 = <!-- {{ICD10|Xxx.x}} --> | ICD9 = <!-- {{ICD9|xxx}} --> | ICDO = | OMIM = | MedlinePlus = | MeSH = | GeneReviewsNBK = | GeneReviewsName = }}
An '''intestinal parasite infection''' is a condition in which a [[parasite]] infects the [[gastro-intestinal tract]] of humans and other animals. Such parasites can live anywhere in the body, but most prefer the intestinal wall.
Routes of exposure and infection include ingestion of undercooked meat, drinking infected water, [[fecal-oral transmission]] and skin absorption.
Some types of [[helminths]] and [[protozoa]] are classified as intestinal parasites that cause infection—those that reside in the [[intestines]]. These infections can damage or sicken the host (humans or other animals). If the intestinal parasite infection is caused by helminths, the infection is called [[helminthiasis]].
==Signs and symptoms== Signs and symptoms depend on the type of infection. Intestinal parasites produce a variety of symptoms in those affected, most of which manifest themselves in gastrointestinal complications and general weakness.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/intestinal_worms/more/en/|title=Intestinal worms|website=World Health Organization|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-03-28}}</ref> Gastrointestinal complications include diarrhea, nausea, [[dysentery]], and abdominal pain. These symptoms negatively impact nutritional status, including decreased absorption of [[micronutrient]]s, loss of appetite, weight loss, and intestinal blood loss that can often result in [[anemia]]. It may also cause physical and mental disabilities, [[delayed growth]] in children, and skin irritation around the anus and vulva.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ashtiani|first=M. T. H.|last2=Monajemzadeh|first2=M.|last3=Saghi|first3=B.|last4=Shams|first4=S.|last5=Mortazavi|first5=S. H.|last6=Khaki|first6=S.|last7=Mohseni|first7=N.|last8=Kashi|first8=L.|last9=Nikmanesh|first9=B.|date=2011-10-01|year=|title=Prevalence of intestinal parasites among children referred to Children’s Medical Center during 18 years (1991–2008), Tehran, Iran|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1179/1364859411Y.0000000040|journal=Annals of Tropical Medicine & Parasitology|volume=105|issue=7|pages=507–513|doi=10.1179/1364859411Y.0000000040|issn=0003-4983|pmc=4100314|pmid=22185945|via=}}</ref>
== Cause == {{See also|Helminthiasis|Schistosomiasis}}
The prevalence of intestinal parasites is the highest among children that are living in the poorest communities in developing nations.<ref name=":0" /> The most common causes of intestinal parasites are through consumption of contaminated water, infected soil, inadequate sanitation and hygiene, and improper hygiene.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ziegelbauer|first=Kathrin|last2=Speich|first2=Benjamin|last3=Mäusezahl|first3=Daniel|last4=Bos|first4=Robert|last5=Keiser|first5=Jennifer|last6=Utzinger|first6=Jürg|date=2012-01-24|year=|title=Effect of Sanitation on Soil-Transmitted Helminth Infection: Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosmedicine/article?id=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001162|journal=PLOS Medicine|volume=9|issue=1|pages=e1001162|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001162|issn=1549-1676|pmc=3265535|pmid=22291577|via=}}</ref> Specifically, lack of access to facilities for safe disposal of human waste can result in intestinal parasites and disease. Poor hygiene habits or lacking available hygiene resources, such as [[hand washing]] facilities, also negatively impact rates of disease.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cairncross|first=Sandy|last2=Bartram|first2=Jamie|last3=Cumming|first3=Oliver|last4=Brocklehurst|first4=Clarissa|date=2010-11-16|year=|title=Hygiene, Sanitation, and Water: What Needs to Be Done?|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosmedicine/article?id=10.1371/journal.pmed.1000365|journal=PLOS Medicine|volume=7|issue=11|pages=e1000365|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1000365|issn=1549-1676|pmc=2981587|pmid=21125019|via=}}</ref> Parasitic contamination can also occur from eating raw vegetables and fruits,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bekele|first=Fitsum|last2=Tefera|first2=Tamirat|last3=Biresaw|first3=Gelila|last4=Yohannes|first4=Tsegaye|date=2017-01-01|year=|title=Parasitic contamination of raw vegetables and fruits collected from selected local markets in Arba Minch town, Southern Ethiopia|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1186/s40249-016-0226-6|journal=Infectious Diseases of Poverty|volume=6|pages=19|doi=10.1186/s40249-016-0226-6|issn=2049-9957|pmc=5340032|pmid=28264707|via=}}</ref> [[geophagia|soil-eating behaviour]],<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Freeman|first=M. C.|last2=Chard|first2=A. N.|last3=Nikolay|first3=B.|last4=Garn|first4=J. V.|last5=Okoyo|first5=C.|last6=Kihara|first6=J.|last7=Njenga|first7=S. M.|last8=Pullan|first8=R. L.|last9=Brooker|first9=S. J.|date=2015-01-01|year=|title=Associations between school- and household-level water, sanitation and hygiene conditions and soil-transmitted helminth infection among Kenyan school children|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1186/s13071-015-1024-x|journal=Parasites & Vectors|volume=8|pages=412|doi=10.1186/s13071-015-1024-x|issn=1756-3305|pmc=4528701|pmid=26248869|via=}}</ref> and lack of available safe water.<ref name=":1" />
Parasites can get into the intestine by going through the mouth from uncooked or unwashed food, contaminated [[water]] or hands, or by [[skin]] contact with [[larva]] infected [[soil]]; they can also be transferred by the sexual act of [[anilingus]] in some cases. When the organisms are swallowed, they move into the intestine, where they can reproduce and cause symptoms. Children are particularly susceptible if they are not thoroughly cleaned after coming into contact with infected soil that is present in environments that they may frequently visit such as sandboxes and school playgrounds. People in developing countries are also at particular risk due to drinking water from sources that may be contaminated with parasites that colonize the gastrointestinal tract.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}
== Diagnosis == [[File:Cryptosporidium muris.jpg|thumb|Cryptosporidium muris]] Due to the wide variety of intestinal parasites, a description of the symptoms rarely is sufficient for diagnosis. Instead, medical personnel use one of two common tests: they search stool samples for the parasites, or apply an adhesive to the [[anus]] to search for eggs. ===Types=== Major groups of parasites include [[protozoan]]s (organisms having only one cell) and [[helminths|parasitic worm]]s (helminths). Of these, protozoans, including [[cryptosporidium]], [[microsporidia]], and [[isospora]], are most common in [[HIV]]-infected persons. Each of these parasites can infect the digestive tract, and sometimes two or more can cause infection at the same time.
==Prevention and intervention== Good hygiene is necessary to avoid reinfection. [[The Rockefeller Foundation]]'s hookworm campaign in Mexico in the 1920s was extremely effective at eliminating hookworm from humans with the use of [[anthelmintic]]s. However, preventative measures were not adequately introduced to the people that were treated. Therefore, the rate of reinfection was extremely high and the project evaluated through any sort of scientific method was a marked failure. More education was needed to inform the people of the importance of wearing shoes, using [[latrines]] (better access to [[sanitation]]), and good hygiene.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Birn, Anne-Emanuelle|author2=Armando Solórzano|year=1999|title=Public health policy paradoxes: science and politics in the Rockefeller Foundation's hookworm campaign in Mexico in the 1920s|journal=Social Science & Medicine|volume=49|issue=9|pages=1197–1213|pmid=10501641|doi=10.1016/S0277-9536(99)00160-4}}</ref>
Intestinal parasite prevention methods are not isolated to specific geographical areas; however, many of the research-based interventions have primarily taken place in underdeveloped countries and regions, where sanitation is a large concern for spreading disease.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}Current best practice behaviors that prevent intestinal parasites include: using proper hand washing practices, using correctly-built latrines with ample ventilation, having a piped water source, and wearing shoes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gelaw|first=Aschalew|last2=Anagaw|first2=Belay|last3=Nigussie|first3=Bethel|last4=Silesh|first4=Betrearon|last5=Yirga|first5=Atnad|last6=Alem|first6=Meseret|last7=Endris|first7=Mengistu|last8=Gelaw|first8=Baye|date=2013-01-01|year=|title=Prevalence of intestinal parasitic infections and risk factors among schoolchildren at the University of Gondar Community School, Northwest Ethiopia: a cross-sectional study|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1186/1471-2458-13-304|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=13|pages=304|doi=10.1186/1471-2458-13-304|issn=1471-2458|pmc=3621079|pmid=23560704|via=}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Abossie|first=Ashenafi|last2=Seid|first2=Mohammed|date=2014-01-01|year=|title=Assessment of the prevalence of intestinal parasitosis and associated risk factors among primary school children in Chencha town, Southern Ethiopia|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1186/1471-2458-14-166|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=14|pages=166|doi=10.1186/1471-2458-14-166|issn=1471-2458|pmc=3933408|pmid=24528627|via=}}</ref> Currently, in some parts of Ethiopia where disease prevalence is high, up to 80% of people in a population lack access to washing facilities. While this is high, 93% did have access to a latrine, but only 29.2% of those latrines had proper construction to decrease parasitic infections.<ref name=":2" />Behavioral interventions have focused on promoting washing, sometimes with soap, in context of education at schools and child care facilities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ejemot-Nwadiaro|first=Regina I|last2=Ehiri|first2=John E|last3=Arikpo|first3=Dachi|last4=Meremikwu|first4=Martin M|last5=Critchley|first5=Julia A|date=2015-09-03|year=|title=Hand washing promotion for preventing diarrhoea|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=|issue=9|pages=1–95|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004265.pub3|issn=1469-493X|pmc=4563982|pmid=26346329|via=}}</ref> In recent studies, the best interventions follow a multidisciplinary approach by: * Increasing environmental sanitation to promote hand washing and shoe wearing habits * Educating children at young ages at school and at home Specific evidence-based interventions that may lower disease prevalence include: * Interventions at schools, focusing on the construction of pit latrines (ventilated and improved), providing clean drinking water and educating the students about hygiene<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gelaye|first=Bizu|last2=Kumie|first2=Abera|last3=Aboset|first3=Nigusu|last4=Berhane|first4=Yemane|last5=Williams|first5=Michelle A.|date=2014-03-01|year=|title=School-based intervention: evaluating the role of water, latrines and hygiene education on trachoma and intestinal parasitic infections in Ethiopia|url=http://washdev.iwaponline.com/content/4/1/120|journal=Journal of Water Sanitation and Hygiene for Development|language=en|volume=4|issue=1|pages=120–130|doi=10.2166/washdev.2013.060|issn=2043-9083|pmc=4387890|pmid=25859318|via=}}</ref>
* The SAFE (surgery, antibiotics, facial cleanliness, environmental sanitation) strategy to address [[trachoma]], primarily the facial cleanliness and the environmental sanitation components<ref>{{Cite journal|last=King|first=Jonathan D.|last2=Endeshaw|first2=Tekola|last3=Escher|first3=Elisabeth|last4=Alemtaye|first4=Genetu|last5=Melaku|first5=Sileabatt|last6=Gelaye|first6=Woyneshet|last7=Worku|first7=Abebe|last8=Adugna|first8=Mitku|last9=Melak|first9=Berhanu|date=2013-06-06|year=|title=Intestinal Parasite Prevalence in an Area of Ethiopia after Implementing the SAFE Strategy, Enhanced Outreach Services, and Health Extension Program|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosntds/article?id=10.1371/journal.pntd.0002223|journal=PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases|volume=7|issue=6|pages=e2223|doi=10.1371/journal.pntd.0002223|issn=1935-2735|pmc=3675016|pmid=23755308|via=}}</ref> * Hand-washing with soap at critical times and nail clipping to decrease reinfection rates, although further research is needed to develop and implement similar interventions at scale{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} * Programs combining anthelmintic drug administration with interventions to increase environmental sanitation (such as decreasing fecal contamination)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steinmann|first=Peter|last2=Yap|first2=Peiling|last3=Utzinger|first3=Jürg|last4=Du|first4=Zun-Wei|last5=Jiang|first5=Jin-Yong|last6=Chen|first6=Ran|last7=Wu|first7=Fang-Wei|last8=Chen|first8=Jia-Xu|last9=Zhou|first9=Hui|date=2015-01-01|title=Control of soil-transmitted helminthiasis in Yunnan province, People's Republic of China: Experiences and lessons from a 5-year multi-intervention trial|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0001706X14003131|journal=Acta Tropica|series=Progress in research and control of helminth infections in Asia|volume=141, Part B|pages=271–280|doi=10.1016/j.actatropica.2014.10.001}}</ref>
== Treatment == {{see also|Helminthiasis#Treatment}} [[File:Praziquantel.svg|thumb|150 px|Praziquantel]] Drugs are frequently used to kill parasites in the host. In earlier times, [[turpentine]] was often used for this, but modern drugs do not poison intestinal worms directly. Rather, anthelmintic drugs now inhibit an enzyme that is necessary for the worm to make the substance that prevents the worm from being digested.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}
For example, [[tapeworm]]s are usually treated with a medicine taken by mouth. The most commonly used medicine for tapeworms is [[praziquantel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO Model Prescribing Information: Drugs Used in Parasitic Diseases - Second Edition: Helminths: Cestode (tapeworm) infection|url=http://apps.who.int/medicinedocs/en/d/Jh2922e/3.html|website=apps.who.int|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref>
== References == {{Reflist}} ==Further reading== *{{cite journal|last1=Feary|first1=J.|last2=Britton|first2=J.|last3=Leonardi-Bee|first3=J.|title=Atopy and current intestinal parasite infection: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=Allergy|date=April 2011|volume=66|issue=4|pages=569–578|doi=10.1111/j.1398-9995.2010.02512.x|issn=1398-9995|pmid=21087217}} {{Medicine|state=collapsed}} [[Category:Gastrointestinal tract disorders]] [[Category:Parasites of animals]]

