{{Infobox lake | name = Lower Nihotupu Reservoir | image = Lower Nihotupu storage lake from Nihotupu bush tram line.jpg | caption = Looking south, the reservoir from the Rainforest Express bush tram line. | image_bathymetry = | caption_bathymetry = | location = [[Auckland]], [[North Island]] | coords = {{coord|-36.9588|174.6132|type:waterbody_region:NZ|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | type = [[Reservoir]] | inflow = | outflow = | catchment = | basin_countries = New Zealand | length = | width = | area = {{convert|52.9|ha|abbr=on}}<ref name=watercare>[http://www.watercare.co.nz/about-watercare/our-services/hunua-and-waitakere-dams-water/Pages/default.aspx] (from the Water Care Services website. Accessed 2013-09-24.)</ref> | depth = | max-depth = | volume = {{convert|4.60|-|4.81|e6m3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}<ref name="To 1990"/><ref name=watercare/> | residence_time = | shore = | elevation = | islands = | cities = }}
The '''Lower Nihotupu Reservoir''' (or '''Lower Nihotupu Dam''') is one of five [[reservoirs]] in the [[Waitakere Ranges]] that supply [[water]] to [[Auckland Region|Auckland]]. Built between 1945 and 1948,<ref name="To 1990">''Engineering to 1990'' — [[Institution of Professional Engineers New Zealand|IPENZ]], Engineering Publications Co Ltd, Page 8-9</ref> the reservoir covers an area of 52.9 hectares and has a capacity of 4.6 million cubic metres.<ref name=watercare /> The reservoir is managed by [[Water Care Services Limited]], a [[City council|council]]-owned company.
The dam is credited as one of the first applied examples of the [[soil mechanics]] science in New Zealand, and was soon followed by the creating of engineering geology as a major subject at the School of Engineering, Auckland.<ref name="To 1990"/>
