{{Infobox person | name = Nobukazu Kuriki | image = | caption = | native_name = 栗城 史多 | native_name_lang = ja | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1982|6|9}} | birth_place = [[Imakane, Hokkaido|Imakane]], [[Setana District, Hokkaido]], Japan | nationality = Japanese | death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|5|21|1982|6|9}} | alias = | occupation = Mountaineer, entrepreneur | years_active = | death_place = [[Mt. Everest]], [[Nepal]] | agent = Yoshimoto Creative Agency | height = | spouse = | relatives = | website = {{official website|http://kurikiyama.jp/}} }} {{nihongo|'''Nobukazu Kuriki'''|栗城 史多|Kuriki Nobukazu|June 9, 1982 – May 21, 2018<ref>https://www.excite.co.jp/News/it_g/20180521/Itmedia_news_20180521082.html</ref>}} was a Japanese mountaineer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/entertainment/2017859/full/|title=栗城史多氏、エベレスト登頂断念 4度目山頂アタックも無念の下山|language=ja|accessdate=September 26, 2015|work=Oricon Style|trans-title=Mr. Furuta Kurisaki, abandoned Everest climb for the fourth time Shimoyama who is also unfortunate of mountaintop attacks}}</ref> and entrepreneur. He was known for his unusual climbing style, typically climbing solo and without supplementary oxygen.<ref name="nippon.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.nippon.com/en/people/e00016/|title=“Sharing My Adventures” With the World|work=Nippon.com|date=13 July 2012|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref><ref name="Alan Arnette 2018">{{cite web|url=http://www.alanarnette.com/blog/2018/05/20/everest-2018-dead-on-everest-japanese-alpinist-nobukazu-kuriki/|title=Everest 2018: Dead on Everest Japanese Alpinist Nobukazu Kuriki|work=The Blog on alanarnette.com|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>
==Early life== Kuriki was born in [[Imakane, Hokkaido|Imakane]], [[Setana District, Hokkaido]], Japan.<ref>May 6, 2012 broadcast of ''The Nonfiction'', [[Fuji Television]]</ref> He graduated from Hokkaido Hiyama Kita High School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.econakoto.net/kuriki/article/186|title=www.econakoto.net|language=ja|accessdate=September 26, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924211331/http://www.econakoto.net/kuriki/article/186|archivedate=September 24, 2015|df=}}</ref> and [[Sapporo International University]]'s Humanities and Sociology Department of Sociology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siu.ac.jp/06shushoku/old/2141.html|title=卒業生（栗城史多）のインタビュー記事・2007年|language=ja|publisher=Sapporo International University|accessdate=September 26, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
== Mountain climbing== Kuriki climbed the [[Himalayas]] at high altitude once or twice a year. He successfully climbed the [[Eight-thousander|8000 meter peaks]] [[Cho Oyu]] in August 2007 and [[Dhaulagiri]] in May 2009.<ref name="Alan Arnette 2018"/> He tried to climb [[Mount Everest]] without oxygen while live streaming over the internet, climbing the [[Tibet]] side in September 2009, and the Nepal side in September 2010, but was not able to climb above 8,000 meters. In his third time climbing the Nepal side in August to October 2011, Kuriki was not able to reach 7,900 meters. During his fourth attempt in October 2012, he gave up due to the strong wind, and lost nine of his fingers to frostbite after spending two days in a [[Snow cave|snow hole]] at temperatures below -20°C.<ref>{{cite news|title=Japanese climber who lost nine fingers to frostbite nears summit of Everest|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/nepal/11894059/Japanese-climber-who-lost-nine-fingers-to-frostbite-nears-summit-of-Everest.html|accessdate=10 January 2016|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> His 2015 attempt was prevented by the [[2015 Mount Everest avalanches|avalanche]] that struck Everest Base Camp that year, and his attempts in 2016 and 2017 were cut short by weather conditions.<ref name="Alan Arnette 2018"/>
He gave well-attended lectures across Japan on the theme of "shared adventure" and the value of perseverance<ref name="nippon.com"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/21/world/asia/nobukazu-kuriki-everest-death.html|title=Death of Japanese Climber on Everest Raises Toll This Month to 3|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref>, and attracted numerous social media followers with his online postings, including videos and photos of his climbs.<ref name="Alan Arnette 2018"/>
Kuriki successfully climbed the highest peaks of 6 continents (the [[Seven Summits]]) during his career, including [[Denali]], [[Mount Aconcagua]], [[Mount Elbrus]], [[Mount Kilimanjaro]], the [[Carstensz Pyramid]], and [[Mount Vinson]].<ref name="Japan Times"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/05/21/he-lost-his-fingers-trying-to-climb-everest-on-his-eighth-attempt-he-lost-his-life/|title=He lost his fingers trying to climb Everest. On his eighth attempt, he lost his life.|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://7summitsclub.com/newssections/all_1/object_7_1/newssection_3_1/item_1379/|title=Solo climber scales 6th of `7 summits`|work=7 Summits Club|date=31 December 2007|accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref>
He was represented by the talent agency, Yoshimoto Creative Agency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://career.oricon.co.jp/news/2001095/full/|title=登山家・栗城史多氏が吉本と業務提携 3度目のエベレスト遠征へ 2011年08月25日|language=ja|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=September 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yoshimotonews.laff.jp/news/2011/08/post-a4de.html|title=エベレスト無酸素・単独登頂に挑戦する登山家・栗城史多さんがよしもとと業務提携!! 2011年8月25日|language=ja|publisher=Yoshimoto News Center|accessdate=September 26, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817044311/http://yoshimotonews.laff.jp/news/2011/08/post-a4de.html|archivedate=August 17, 2014|df=}}</ref>
===Death=== In May 2018, during his 8th attempt to climb [[Mount Everest]], he died while descending from Camp Three after abandoning the attempt due to illness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Climber Nobukazu Kuriki dies on Mt. Everest|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180521_32/|accessdate=21 May 2018|publisher=NHK World - Japan}}</ref><ref name="Japan Times">{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/05/21/national/top-alpinist-kuriki-dies-eighth-attempt-conquer-everest/|title=Top alpinist Nobukazu Kuriki dies in eighth attempt to conquer Everest|work=The Japan Times|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> He is survived by his father Toshio. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockandice.com/climbing-news/seventh-times-the-charm-kuriki-poised-for-everest-summit|title=Seventh's Time the Charm? Kuriki Poised for Everest Summit|work=Rock and Ice Magazine|date=10 May 2017|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>
